Tests `ctx_cage::proxy`: HTTP CONNECT-less head rewriting (owned headers replaced, rest passed through) plus one end-to-end connection served over `UnixStream::pair()` sockets against a fake upstream, and a `serve()`-level check that dial failures are written to `cfg.log_path` rather than stderr.

Key fact motivating the last test: during an interactive cage run, the proxy process's stderr is the raw-mode host terminal — writing errors there directly corrupts the PTY relay's display, so `serve`'s per-connection failure branch must go through the log file exclusively. This is asserted by polling the log file for "connection failed" (`wait_for_log_contains`), not by capturing stderr.

`rewrite_head(head, &ProxyConfig)` is exercised for both key-injection mode (`api_key: Some(..)` swaps `Host`/`x-api-key`, forces `Connection: close`, strips any client `Authorization`) and passthrough mode (`api_key: None` preserves the client's own `Authorization: Bearer ...` OAuth header untouched). Output always ends `\r\n\r\n`.

`FakeUpstream` implements `Upstream` by handing back one end of a `UnixStream::pair()` and stashing the other end in a `Mutex<Option<UnixStream>>` for the test to retrieve via `take_server_end` (polls up to 1s). `serve_conn_rewrites_forwards_and_relays_the_response` drives a full request/response cycle through `serve_conn` on real socketpairs, checking rewritten headers, forwarded body, and relayed response arrive intact.

`FailingUpstream` always errors from `connect()`, used only to trigger `serve`'s logging path. `bind_serve_fixture` binds a fresh Unix socket path and returns listener + config; cleanup of socket and log files is manual (`std::fs::remove_file`) at test end — no `Drop` guard, so a panicking assertion mid-test can leak tempfiles (`fresh_tempfile`/`fresh_socket_path` use an atomic counter plus PID to avoid collisions across parallel test runs, not to avoid leaks).